This well-known organism has been reported on numerous occasions from sites all over the world and thus its identity is relatively easy to establish (
Stein, 1867
; 
Kahl, 1932
; 
Suzuki, 1954
; 
Bhandary, 1962
; 
Cela, 1972
; 
Dragesco & Dragesco-Kernéis, 1991
; 
Lee & Shin, 2009
). The Qingdao population corresponds closely with both the original report (
Stein, 1867
) and the redescription by 
Kahl (1932)
in terms of its bright pink coloration and the pinkish cortical granules, general morphology, pattern of ciliature, possession of two macronuclear nodules, and habitat (
Fig. 6
; 
Table 4
).
